#!/bin/sh
# Module 04 — quick reference, shown by the `labhelp` command.
cat <<'EOF'

  MODULE 04 — Cryptography                    (you are analyst@station)
  -------------------------------------------------------------------

  MISSION
    Part A: break an intercepted classic cipher and see why simple
            substitution can't stand up to a computer.
    Part B: use real public-key crypto (GnuPG/PGP) — encrypt a message
            only the recipient can read, and sign one to prove who sent it.

  PART A — CLASSIC CIPHERS  (real cipher tool — run them, read the output)

    cat challenge.txt                     show the intercepted ciphertext

    cipher break "$(cat challenge.txt)"   try all 25 Caesar shifts (crack it)
    cipher shift 3 HELLO                   shift text forward by 3
    cipher atbash CRYPTOGRAPHY             apply the Atbash cipher

  PART B — PUBLIC-KEY (PGP) with two people, Alice and Bob

    sh make-keys.sh                        create Alice's and Bob's key pairs
    gpg --list-keys                        list the keys in the keyring

    # encrypt a message so ONLY Bob can read it (uses Bob's public key)
    printf '%s' "meet at the docks at midnight" \
      | gpg --yes --armor --trust-model always -r bob@lab -e -o message.asc
    cat message.asc                        the scrambled PGP MESSAGE block

    gpg --yes -d message.asc               decrypt it (needs Bob's private key)

    # Alice signs a message with her PRIVATE key; anyone verifies with her public
    printf '%s' "I approve the transfer" \
      | gpg --yes --clearsign -u alice@lab -o signed.asc
    gpg --verify signed.asc                check the signature

    # integrity: flip one character of the ciphertext, then try to decrypt
    sed -i '3s/./X/' message.asc
    gpg --yes -d message.asc               it now fails — that's the point

  TIP
    The cipher tool is deliberately weak — that's the lesson. GnuPG is the real
    thing: the same commands sign software releases and encrypt email in the wild.

  Full lab guide:  module-04-cryptography/LAB-GUIDE.md (in the course files)
  Type  labhelp  any time to see this again.  Type  exit  to leave the lab.

EOF
